The GRE (Graduate Record Exam) is often required of those who aspire to go further after earning an undergraduate degree.  I took it 5 years after getting my B.S. Ed. (And 9 years after my last college math course.)  It was actually interesting (kind of a souped-up SAT.)  
From everything I've (casually) read about British education and university studies, it's quite different.  I don't know about NOW, but for a long time, the USA attracted many foreign students seeking to pursue graduate studies.

@Mean Old Lady
There's no such thing as the GRE, the SAT for that matter. You get accepted onto a degree course on the basis of your school A (Advanced) level exam passes at 17/18, usually 4 subjects, at A, B, C etc. For a non-science course, no maths is necessary after age 16. For science courses, no pass in English is required after age 16. So students usually stop doing any maths/English at 16, depending on their choices. 

 You get accepted on to post-graduate courses on the strength of your undergraduate degree. The biggest hurdle is finding the funding!

@Marcia Fidler

You will rarely see a complaint about Monday, Tuesday or Wednesday being too easy.  They're supposed to be straightforward.  Every once in a while, some people find them too difficult for the day, and will point that out.

The real complaints come in when Thursday, Friday and Saturday puzzles are not challenging, or when they are appropriately challenging.  Experienced solvers will object to the former, while a subset of newer ones will not like the latter.  Some newer solvers appreciate that they are not quite ready to succeed, and know that they will have to work to get there.

